Nuvio QA Automation Framework

UI and API automation framework built with Playwright, NUnit and .NET 9 for testing the Nuvio CMS (PocketBase-based backend written in Go).

The project is designed as a scalable automation architecture, supporting:

Parallel test execution

CI/CD integration

Playwright tracing

Automatic screenshot capture

Environment configuration

Dockerized application testing

Generic CRUD testing for PocketBase collections

Architecture

The framework follows a layered architecture designed for maintainability and scalability.

Framework
 ├ Engine
 │   ├ BrowserManager
 │   ├ ContextManager
 │   ├ PlaywrightEngine
 │   ├ ExecutionSettings
 │   └ EnvironmentManager
 │
 ├ Core
 │   ├ TestLifecycleManager
 │   ├ BaseTest
 │   ├ Waiter
 │   ├ RetryHandler
 │   └ ElementExecutor
 │
 ├ Assertions
 │   └ UiAssert
 │
Application
 ├ UI
 │   ├ Pages
 │   ├ Components
 │   └ Context
 │
Tests
 └ UI
     └ CollectionCrudTests

Design Goals

Clear separation of concerns

Reusable UI components

Minimal test logic duplication

Environment driven configuration

CI/CD friendly execution

Test Lifecycle

Each test follows this lifecycle:

TestLifecycleManager
        │
        ▼
Shared Browser (BrowserManager)
        │
        ▼
New Browser Context per Test
        │
        ▼
Page + UI Components
        │
        ▼
Assertions

Key properties:

Single browser instance

Isolated contexts per test

Parallel execution ready

Technologies
Tool	Purpose
.NET 9	Test runtime
Playwright	Browser automation
NUnit	Test framework
GitHub Actions	CI/CD
Docker	Environment orchestration
PocketBase	Backend being tested
Features
Parallel UI Testing

Tests can run in parallel using NUnit.

Example:

dotnet test --filter "Category=UI"

Parallelization happens at the test level using isolated browser contexts.

Artifact Capture

When a test fails, the framework automatically generates debugging artifacts.

Screenshots
artifacts/screenshots/<testname>.png

Captured automatically when:

Test fails

Test category = UI

Playwright Traces
artifacts/traces/<testname>.zip

These can be opened with:

npx playwright show-trace trace.zip
Environment Configuration

Configuration is controlled via environment variables.

Variable	Description
BASE_URL	Application URL
HEADLESS	Run browser headless
ADMIN_USER	PocketBase admin login
ADMIN_PASSWORD	PocketBase admin password
TRACING	Enable Playwright tracing
SCREENSHOT_ON_FAILURE	Enable screenshots
ARTIFACT_DIR	Artifact output folder

Example:

BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8090
HEADLESS=true
ADMIN_USER=admin@example.com
ADMIN_PASSWORD=secret
Running Tests Locally
Install dependencies
dotnet restore
dotnet build

Install Playwright browsers:

pwsh bin/Debug/net9.0/playwright.ps1 install
Run UI tests
dotnet test --filter "Category=UI"
CI/CD Pipeline

Tests run automatically using GitHub Actions.

Pipeline steps:

Checkout automation repository

Checkout Nuvio application repository

Install Go runtime

Start Nuvio server

Install .NET

Build automation project

Install Playwright browsers

Run UI tests

Upload artifacts

Artifacts stored:

Playwright traces

Failure screenshots

Nuvio server logs

Docker Support

Nuvio can be run inside Docker for consistent environments.

Build and run:

docker compose up --build

This starts the Nuvio server inside a container and exposes it on:

http://localhost:8090

This allows the automation framework to test the application in an isolated environment.

Example Test

Example CRUD test:

[Test]
[Category("UI")]
public async Task CreateUser_ShouldAppearInGrid()
{
    await CollectionContext.CreateAsync(
        "users",
        new UserData
        {
            Email = "test@example.com",
            Password = "Password123!"
        });

    await CollectionContext.AssertRowMatchesAsync(
        "users",
        "email",
        "test@example.com");
}
